05118nam a22009495i 9780228013044DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280130447 a10.1515/97802280130442doi  a(DE-B1597)656060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJN6639.A2bK56 2022 7aPOL0580002bisacsh04a323.62231 aKnott, Eleanor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKin Majorities :bIdentity and Citizenship in Crimea and Moldova /cEleanor Knott. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Usages and Transliteration -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- tKin-State Politics through the Identity-Citizenship Nexus -- tCrimea and Moldova as Kin Majorities -- tTo Be Discriminated Against, or Not, in Crimea -- tNeither Russian Citizens nor Compatriots -- tTo Be Nested, or Not, in Moldova -- tFrom Nested Identities to Nested Citizens -- tIdentity, Citizenship, and Kin Majorities -- tA Note on Methods and Methodology -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Moldova, the number of dual citizens has risen exponentially in the last decades. Before annexation, many saw Russia as granting citizenship to—or passportizing—large numbers in Crimea. Both are regions with kin majorities: local majorities claimed as co-ethnic by external states offering citizenship, among other benefits. As functioning citizens of the states in which they reside, kin majorities do not need to acquire citizenship from an external state. Yet many do so in high numbers.Kin Majorities explores why these communities engage with dual citizenship and how this intersects, or not, with identity. Analyzing data collected from ordinary people in Crimea and Moldova in 2012 and 2013, just before Russia’s annexation of Crimea, Eleanor Knott provides a crucial window into Russian identification in a time of calm. Perhaps surprisingly, the discourse and practice of Russian citizenship was largely absent in Crimea before annexation. Comparing the situation in Crimea with the strong presence of Romanian citizenship in Moldova, Knott explores two rarely researched cases from the ground up, shedding light on why Romanian citizenship was more prevalent and popular in Moldova than Russian citizenship in Crimea, and to what extent identity helps explain the difference.Kin Majorities offers a fresh and nuanced perspective on how citizenship interacts with cross-border and local identities, with crucial implications for the politics of geography, nation, and kin-states, as well as broader understandings of post-Soviet politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCitizenshipzMoldova. 0aCitizenshipzUkrainezCrimea. 0aDual nationalityzMoldova. 0aDual nationalityzUkrainezCrimea. 0aGeopoliticszMoldova. 0aGeopoliticszUkrainezCrimea. 0aGroup identityzMoldova. 0aGroup identityzUkrainezCrimea. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / European.2bisacsh  aEastern Europe.  aMoldovan.  aPassport.  aRomania.  aRussia.  aSoviet Union.  aUkraine.  aacquisition.  aannexation.  abottom up.  acase study.  acitizenship.  acomparative.  acompatriot.  adiscrimination.  adual.  aeducation.  aethnicity.  aeveryday.  ageneration.  aidentification.  ainterviews.  akin state.  alanguage.  anation.  anationalism.  aperiphery.  apolicy.  apolitical science.  apost soviet.  aqualitative research.  aquasi-citizenship.  arights.  ascholarships.40uhttps://d